			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Dropped LDoN augments<a name="28074"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 16 04 11:26 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>This is a hard question.  What you're really asking is -- what role does NBG play in a pick-up group.
<br />

<br />
Now, the prior poster is right - some Shammies do think they use charisma.  I do not know if they're right or wrong.  I will assume, because it makes the argument more interesting, that they're wrong.
<br />

<br />
I will also assume that what you're describing is a pick-up group.  I assume that based on the &quot;strange sort of people who don't talk&quot; comment.
<br />

<br />
My question is--why would people in a pick-up group apply NBG?
<br />

<br />
Before we get sidetracked, let me make clear:  I don't do pick-up groups.  My regular group is VERY strongly NBG.  Very strongly.  To give an example -- a week or so ago, we took a pickup cleric into a hard MMC because our regular healer wasn't available.  Those plate boots dropped and we all automatically rolled for them.  They've dropped for us so often that we now just knee-jerk that they're bazaar bait.  Pick up cleric mentions that they'd be an upgrade for him and links his current boots -- which truly did suck.  Despite getting the low roll, he got the boots.  So, I do not need to be persuaded that NBG is the superior system for repeat groups or guild groups.  I think that in a utopia, it would even be the superior system for pick-up groups, but we don't play in a utopia.
<br />

<br />
Repeat or guild groups mean all members are repeat players.  NBG makes sense for them.  If I give up a good weapon to the warrior today, I know someone else will be giving up an INT or mana item to me later on.  Etc. etc.  And, I also know that the warrior having the superior weapon will help the group overall.
<br />

<br />
I don't see the same incentives working in a pick-up group.  
<br />

<br />

<br />
As a separate and independent issue, I also don't see where the pick-up group can be relied on to honestly evaluate need.  In my regular group, those cross-incentives mean people don't fib about what they would use.  Nobody who doesn't really need CHA will say they need CHA, because everybody knows that getting my CHA up means better pulls etc.  Nobody who doesn't really need INT will say they need INT because they know neither I nor the Wiz have maxxed our INT.  Etc.
<br />

<br />
In a pick-up group, what stops someone from just lying?  And if you can't rely on people to honestly evaluate what they need, how does NBG work?
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
