				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Dropped LDoN augments<a name="28634"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 18 04 11:56 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Sure.  I don't mean to suggest that there aren't very knowledgable and well-played shammies who hold the contrary view.
<br />

<br />
The shaman I regularly group with has been playing a shaman nonstop for a bit over three years now (she's still bound at the firepots in TD -- I can't convince her to rebind.  I think it's a point of pride).  Level 65, only about 100 AAs but that's because she hates exp grinding and would much prefer to spend an evening trying to figure out which dragons in WW she can solo.  
<br />

<br />
My point is that it's not a settled issue.  At least, not settled enough that I'd balk at a shaman wanting a CHA drop.
<br />

<br />
As an aside, shammies as a class are the most superstitious EQ players alive.  At one time or another, I have heard the following theories propounded on the shammy boards:
<br />

<br />
* Smithing succeeds more if your wisdom is even rather than odd
<br />
* Alchemy succeeds more if you have the alchemy book open when you combine
<br />
* Turgurs lands more if you have high CHA
<br />
* Turgurs lands more if you're within melee range
<br />
* Barbs should turn in parchments/words during the day, Ogres, Trolls, and Iksar should turn in at night
<br />
* Killing COM mobs in a particular order affects the spawn of the lower level epic mob
<br />
</span></td>
