			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Dropped LDoN augments<a name="28930"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 19 04 1:07 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Nah people on the Crucible are generally fairly civilized.  They have a few pissbuckets, but the norm of conduct there is quite good.
<br />

<br />
In any event, the fact that it's been &quot;done to death&quot; supports the point that the shaman in the original narrative isn't just a selfish greedy little sleeze.  Even if someone did post a parse that debunks the argument (sidebar -- I question the methodology as explained below) the fact that the issue was debated that heavily lets me believe the shammy in question was acting in good faith.  Given the number of bards who STILL believe getting KEI will help them regen their mana, I have no trouble believing that this shaman was -- at best -- confused.
<br />

<br />
Methodology:  I recall the post you're describing.  I am not convinced a single parse against a single target is dispositive.  The effect, if there is one, may scale to resist rates.  I analogize to the putative AC softcap.  Lots of monks think there's an AC softcap of 1500.  Lots of others make an EXTREMELY compelling argument:  AC gives diminishing returns once it exceeds the mob's ATK.  All the evidence of a 1500 softcap comes from the same standard parse mob.  Therefore, all the softcap parses prove is that the parse mob has an ATK at or slightly under 1500.
<br />

<br />
Why wouldn't the same be true of the troll's parse?  Maybe CHA affects resist rates measurably under some circumstances -- sham level =&gt; mob level, or mob resist &lt;= some figure, or whatever.
<br />

<br />
Show me a series of parses testing against lots of mobs with lots of levels and resists and you might make a believer out of me.  Otherwise, I'm not so quick to discount the anecdotal experiences of the shammies who do believe it helps them.  /shrug.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
